                    _t('Sentence Variety as a Tool', 'Varying sentence length and structure prevents monotony, creates emphasis, and controls the reader\'s experience of pacing.', 'Reading your essay aloud is the fastest way to detect monotonous sentence rhythm — if all sentences sound the same length and structure, vary them.', 'AP® essays: sentence variety contributes to style control; essays where every sentence follows the same pattern feel less sophisticated regardless of analytical quality.'),
                    _t('Precision in Word Choice', 'Precision means choosing the word that exactly captures the intended meaning — not the most impressive word, not the first word that comes to mind.', '"This shows..." can almost always be replaced with a more precise verb: "demonstrates," "reveals," "exposes," "challenges," "complicates" — each has a different exact meaning.', 'AP®: revise vague verbs ("shows," "talks about," "says") to precise ones that capture exactly what the writer is doing rhetorically.'),
